Could you follow the below listes step in order to get a better knowledge of the steps the lead to this misbehaviour: Before you type "shutdown -r" issue the following commands.
# com-chroot setparameter debug # com-chroot setparameter step halt_stopclusterfs # shutdown -r
The first command sets the shutdown/reboot process to debug mode (found in dmesg or syslogserver if remote syslog is switched on). The second command breaks at the end of the shutdown process and leaves you in a shell environment (this is only necessary if you have no remote syslog enabled).

Neither a stop in a shell nor a different behavior can be observed.
The server is powered off at the end of the shutdown -r command
Regards,
Rudi

Ok, so the problem was that due to a recent change in the standard /var/run had to be created as bindmount (multipathd would not start otherwise, holds only for RHEL5). But unfortunately the /var/run was umounted before the shutdown script (/opt/atix/comoonics-bootimage/boot-scripts/com-halt.sh) was executed. This script uses runlevel to detect the current runlevel and derive the shutdown command from it.
The runlevel command needs /var/run/utmp to detect the runlevel. But it is not there any more. So the com-halt falls back to halt. Which could be observed.
The solution is pretty easy we just need to prevent /var/run from being umounted. This can be done be autoadding /var/run to /etc/xtab (file that excludes all path in there from being umounted).
These are two lines to linuxrc.generic.sh (in the initrd).

bug.short_desc: Systems with multiple different nics get mixed up the network configuration while booting
bug.cf_releasenotes: The automatic detection of the network interfaces has been rewritten/modified so that only the relevant network interface will be configured and will be stabilized during multiple reboots.

long_desc.thetext:
Description of problem: Because of the hw detection in the initrd it happens that nics are detected in different orders. This might mix up the network settings and end up in a failed booting.
How reproducible: Not 100% reproducible but have a system with different nics. Configure one in the initrd and boot multiple time. You might see different mixed up network settings.
Steps to Reproduce: 1. n.a. 2. 3.
Actual results: Sometimes everything is expected (hw detection is done in the right order) and sometime not.
Expected results: MUST always work.
Additional info:

Can be solved by specifying NIC driver in cluster.conf.
Is another solution needed?
yes there is another solution needed. This can lead to different namings.

The explanation seems to be as follows. During hardware detection kudzu triggered an autocreation of all /etc/sysconfig/network-scripts/ifcfg-eth* with MAC Addresses as detected by the kernel (udev?). The order for this is type of detection seems to be not stable in any case.
If the cluster.conf defined eth0 with mac address A and hwdetection detected eth0 with mac address B this lead to a wrong naming of network interfaces and therefore to problems during boot.
So this can be fixed as follows. 1. Kudzu will not be triggered to autoconfigure the network interfaces. This is not required. The configuration is done from the cluster.conf and the detection by udev. This seems to be 100% stable as nics are being renamed if mac addresses are different.
2. The auto configuration of /etc/sysconfig/network-scripts/ifcfg-eth? is made more stable concerning mac addresses. There is the change of mixing the wrong ones into the configuration in multi nic configurations.
Fixes are integrated as follows: com.oonics 4.6: comoonics-bootimage-1.4-79_6 and above com.oonics dev/5.0: comoonics-bootimage-1.4-85 and above

bug.short_desc: It happens, that the cluster gets stuck in activating volume groups
bug.cf_releasenotes:
It can happen, that the cluster stucks inside the initrd when trying to activate lvm volumegroups after cman has been started.
This happens when 3 of nodes are booted at the same time, i.e. without a quorum disk.

long_desc.thetext:
Description of problem: It can happen, that the cluster stucks inside the initrd when trying to activate lvm volumegroups after cman has been started.
Version-Release number of selected component (if applicable):
How reproducible: This happens when 3 of nodes are booted at the same time, i.e. without a quorum disk.
Steps to Reproduce: 1. shutdown the cluster 2. start the cluster 3.
Actual results: cluster habgs in vg activation
Expected results: cluster should boot up
Additional info: This behavior seems to be dependent with the u6 update release.
This behavior has bee observed at bldsrv3-6 at usm. Adding a sleep 10 after starting the clvmd seems to avoid the problem.

This seems to be correlated with either
- cluster inconsistent lvm configuration - multipath configurations - error messages from lvm vgs

In RHEL 4U6 the lvm cache file has been moved from /etc/lvm/cache/.cache to the parent directory: /etc/lvm/.cache
Is it possible that the locking of the .cache file takes longer in the parent directoy?
The clvmd distributes the lvm metadata and maybe if there are multiple nodes entering the cluster at the same time, they all want to write to the cache file?
